China's food safety situation is a growing concern, with tainted food impacting millions annually.
The Asian Development Bank warns of potential disease outbreaks and economic tolls.
The government has implemented measures to improve supervision, but challenges persist.
Experts advocate for a unified food safety mechanism to address loopholes.
Public dissatisfaction with government performance is evident, prompting calls for stricter regulations and accountability.
Recent incidents, including food poisoning cases and contaminated exports, highlight the need for enhanced monitoring and enforcement.
A comprehensive five-year plan aims to strengthen food and drug safety administration nationwide by 2010.
